The paper proposes new models for generating hard random boolean formulas and disjunctive logic programs, which are relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. The use of quantified boolean formulas and logic programs suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and logic (cs.LO). The theoretical bounds and experimental results on the phase transition region and hardness of evaluation suggest a focus on discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the paper's contribution to the development of new models for generating random disjunctive logic programs suggests a focus on programming languages (cs.PL).
